{"id":1427,"date":"2016-06-08T10:43:30","date_gmt":"2016-06-08T09:43:30","guid":{"rendered":"http:\/\/www.edlab.org.uk\/?p=1427"},"modified":"2016-08-31T10:58:09","modified_gmt":"2016-08-31T09:58:09","slug":"funologist-project-use-tinkering-tools-scratch-makey-makey","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/mcrblogs.co.uk\/edlab\/funologist-project-use-tinkering-tools-scratch-makey-makey\/","title":{"rendered":"Funologist Project: Use the Tinkering tools Scratch and Makey Makey"},"content":{"rendered":"<p><strong>Use the Tinkering tools Scratch and Makey Makey to create engaging after school workshops<\/strong><\/p>\n<p>Scratch is a tried and tested tool for exploratory play and learning of coding ideas via tinkering. It\u2019s genesis in MIT labs has ensured it is well supported with wide adoption and an interesting research base. Impressively, the community of users creating and sharing their creations or \u2018scratches\u2019 is significant in size and diversity. There are many remixes of all recognisable computer game types including adventure and narrative forms.<\/p>\n<p><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"aligncenter size-large wp-image-1429\" src=\"http:\/\/mcrblogs.co.uk\/edlab\/wp-content\/uploads\/sites\/64\/2016\/06\/SSPA_01-800x570.jpg\" alt=\"SSPA_01\" width=\"800\" height=\"570\" srcset=\"https:\/\/mcrblogs.co.uk\/edlab\/wp-content\/uploads\/sites\/64\/2016\/06\/SSPA_01-800x570.jpg 800w, https:\/\/mcrblogs.co.uk\/edlab\/wp-content\/uploads\/sites\/64\/2016\/06\/SSPA_01-300x214.jpg 300w, https:\/\/mcrblogs.co.uk\/edlab\/wp-content\/uploads\/sites\/64\/2016\/06\/SSPA_01-768x547.jpg 768w, https:\/\/mcrblogs.co.uk\/edlab\/wp-content\/uploads\/sites\/64\/2016\/06\/SSPA_01-90x65.jpg 90w, https:\/\/mcrblogs.co.uk\/edlab\/wp-content\/uploads\/sites\/64\/2016\/06\/SSPA_01.jpg 1088w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px\" \/><\/p>\n<p>Makey Makey is a keyboard controller interface, which has had great success as a demonstration tool. It is often used in combination with Scratch to showcase the immediacy of new forms of creative software and interactive hardware controllers to create engaging activities.<br \/>\nWe will be working with Code Club who are currently redeveloping their Scratch resource to increase the input and creativity of young people.<\/p>\n<p><!--more--><\/p>\n<p>We can draw on existing understanding of Scratch and the instant engagement of Makey Makey to create our own Scratch activities lead by the interests of young participants. \u00a0Ideally, we\u2019ll go beyond uses of pre-created scratch projects and stimulate young participants to dream up their own playful projects and then help them to make it real.<\/p>\n<p><strong>Our End Goal:<\/strong> We are looking for a group of MMU Students to work with the support of with key academic staff to create a play inspired activity to appeal to young people in the transition from Year 6 to Year 7. It should include issues relevant to young people and include ways for them to express and explore their changing identity.<\/p>\n<p><strong>More Information:<\/strong> Key concepts we are working with here include:<\/p>\n<ul>\n<li>The use of Block Coding to teaching coding fundamentals (Scratch pioneered this approach)<\/li>\n<li>Tinkering with physical objects as way of increasing the engagement of learner<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n<p>To get involved in this project, or to work on a challenge which supports the development of this project, contact m.chesterman@mmu.ac.uk or edlab@mmu.ac.uk<\/p>\n<p>Key Partner: Code Club<\/p>\n<p>Key Words: Primary, Secondary, Home Educators, Code Club, Scratch Software, Tinkering, exploratory play<\/p>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>Use the Tinkering tools Scratch and Makey Makey to create engaging after school workshops Scratch is a tried and tested tool for exploratory play and learning of coding ideas via tinkering. It\u2019s genesis in MIT labs has ensured it is well supported with wide adoption and an interesting research base. Impressively, the community of users [&hellip;]<\/p>\n","protected":false},"author":29,"featured_media":1429,"comment_status":"closed","ping_status":"closed","sticky":false,"template":"","format":"standard","meta":[],"categories":[31,128,1],"tags":[61,190,188,14,189,187,115],"yoast_head":"<!-- This site is optimized with the Yoast SEO plugin v15.6.2 - https:\/\/yoast.com\/wordpress\/plugins\/seo\/ -->\n<meta name=\"robots\" content=\"index, follow, max-snippet:-1, max-image-preview:large, max-video-preview:-1\" \/>\n<link rel=\"canonical\" href=\"https:\/\/mcrblogs.co.uk\/edlab\/funologist-project-use-tinkering-tools-scratch-makey-makey\/\" \/>\n<meta property=\"og:locale\" content=\"en_GB\" \/>\n<meta property=\"og:type\" content=\"article\" \/>\n<meta property=\"og:title\" content=\"Funologist Project: Use the Tinkering tools Scratch and Makey Makey - EdLab MMU\" \/>\n<meta property=\"og:description\" content=\"Use the Tinkering tools Scratch and Makey Makey to create engaging after school workshops Scratch is a tried and tested tool for exploratory play and learning of coding ideas via tinkering. It\u2019s genesis in MIT labs has ensured it is well supported with wide adoption and an interesting research base. Impressively, the community of users [&hellip;]\" \/>\n<meta property=\"og:url\" content=\"https:\/\/mcrblogs.co.uk\/edlab\/funologist-project-use-tinkering-tools-scratch-makey-makey\/\" \/>\n<meta property=\"og:site_name\" content=\"EdLab MMU\" \/>\n<meta property=\"article:published_time\" content=\"2016-06-08T09:43:30+00:00\" \/>\n<meta property=\"article:modified_time\" content=\"2016-08-31T09:58:09+00:00\" \/>\n<meta property=\"og:image\" content=\"https:\/\/mcrblogs.co.uk\/edlab\/wp-content\/uploads\/sites\/64\/2016\/06\/SSPA_01.jpg\" \/>\n\t<meta property=\"og:image:width\" content=\"1088\" \/>\n\t<meta property=\"og:image:height\" content=\"775\" \/>\n<meta name=\"twitter:card\" content=\"summary\" \/>\n<meta name=\"twitter:label1\"